    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stateless vs Stateful LLM Systems"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every LLM API call is itself stateless: the model receives a prompt and returns a completion, with no memory of previous interactions. Whether the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "system",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " built on top of that API is stateless or stateful is a design choice. A stateless system treats every user request as independent; a stateful system maintains conversation history, user preferences, or session context across requests. This distinction has downstream consequences for cost, latency, privacy, scalability, and the quality of multi-turn interactions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Core Difference"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Stateless LLM: Request 2 has no access to Request 1's context, so 'What is my name?' gets no answer. Stateful LLM: session store injects prior turns into Request 2's prompt, correctly answering 'Your name is Alex'."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In the stateless case above, each request is a cold start: the model has no knowledge of what was said before. This is acceptable for single-turn tasks (classification, summarisation of a document) but breaks any multi-turn workflow. In the stateful case, the session store retrieves and injects prior turns, giving the model the context it needs."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to Choose Stateless"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stateless is the right default when the task can be completed in a single exchange and the system does not need to remember anything across requests."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Batch processing",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": each document or record is processed independently \u2014 summarisation, classification, translation."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Single-shot Q&A with RAG",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": the user asks a question, retrieval provides context, the model answers. The conversation ends."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "API-to-API integrations",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": a backend service calls the LLM to transform or enrich data. No user session is involved."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "High-concurrency services",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": stateless servers scale horizontally without synchronising session state. Any server can handle any request."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Stateless is not simpler to implement \u2014 it is simpler to "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "operate",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "italic"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ". No session store to maintain, no cache invalidation, no cross-node session synchronisation. Prefer it when the use case allows."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to Choose Stateful"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stateful design is necessary when the quality of the model's response depends on what happened earlier in the interaction."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Conversational assistants",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": the user refers back to previous messages ('Can you expand on that?', 'Now do the same for option B')."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Multi-step agentic workflows",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": the agent accumulates results across tool calls in a single session."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Personalised experiences",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": the system adapts responses to user preferences collected over prior sessions."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Long-running tasks",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": the user returns to a partially completed task (a document draft, a code review) after an interruption."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stateful Implementation Patterns"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pattern 1: Client-Side State"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest stateful pattern: the client stores the conversation history and sends it with every request. No server-side session store is required. The LLM API treats it as a stateless call with a longer prompt."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from openai import OpenAI\nfrom typing import List\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\ndef chat_session():\n    \"\"\"Simple client-side stateful chat loop.\"\"\\\"\n    history: List[dict] = [\n        {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"You are a helpful assistant.\"}\n    ]\n    while True:\n        user_input = input(\"You: \")\n        if user_input.lower() in (\"quit\", \"exit\"):\n            break\n        history.append({\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_input})\n\n        rsp = client.chat.completions.create(\n            model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n            messages=history,\n        )\n        reply = rsp.choices[0].message.content\n        history.append({\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": reply})\n        print(f\"Assistant: {reply}\")\n    return history\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Client-side state is appropriate for browser-based chat UIs where the conversation is ephemeral and the client is trusted. It is not appropriate when history must survive a page refresh, be accessible from multiple devices, or be stored for audit purposes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pattern 2: Server-Side Session Store"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The server stores conversation history keyed by a session ID. The client sends only the current message; the server loads history, appends the new message, calls the LLM, appends the reply, and persists the updated history."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import json, time, uuid\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom typing import List, Optional\n\n@dataclass\nclass ConversationSession:\n    session_id: str\n    user_id: str\n    messages: List[dict] = field(default_factory=list)\n    created_at: float = field(default_factory=time.time)\n    last_active_at: float = field(default_factory=time.time)\n\n    def add_turn(self, role: str, content: str) -> None:\n        self.messages.append({\"role\": role, \"content\": content})\n        self.last_active_at = time.time()\n\n    @property\n    def token_estimate(self) -> int:\n        total = sum(len(m[\"content\"]) for m in self.messages)\n        return total // 4    # ~4 chars per token\n\nclass SessionStore:\n    \"\"\"In-memory store; replace with Redis or DynamoDB in production.\"\"\\\"\n    def __init__(self, ttl_seconds: int = 3600):\n        self._sessions: dict[str, ConversationSession] = {}\n        self.ttl = ttl_seconds\n\n    def create(self, user_id: str, system_prompt: str) -> ConversationSession:\n        s = ConversationSession(\n            session_id=str(uuid.uuid4()),\n            user_id=user_id,\n            messages=[{\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": system_prompt}],\n        )\n        self._sessions[s.session_id] = s\n        return s\n\n    def get(self, session_id: str) -> Optional[ConversationSession]:\n        s = self._sessions.get(session_id)\n        if s and time.time() - s.last_active_at < self.ttl:\n            return s\n        return None\n\n    def delete(self, session_id: str) -> None:\n        self._sessions.pop(session_id, None)\n\n    def evict_expired(self) -> int:\n        now = time.time()\n        expired = [k for k, v in self._sessions.items()\n                   if now - v.last_active_at >= self.ttl]\n        for k in expired:\n            del self._sessions[k]\n        return len(expired)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pattern 3: Conversation Summarisation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sending the full conversation history grows the prompt (and the cost) linearly with the number of turns. Summarisation compresses old turns into a concise paragraph that is prepended to the system prompt, while keeping only the most recent N turns verbatim."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\ndef summarise_history(\n    messages: list[dict],\n    model: str = \"gpt-4o-mini\",\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Condense a list of chat turns into a paragraph-length summary.\"\"\\\"\n    transcript = \"\\n\".join(\n        f\"{m['role'].upper()}: {m['content']}\"\n        for m in messages\n        if m[\"role\"] != \"system\"\n    )\n    rsp = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=model,\n        messages=[\n            {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\":\n             \"Summarise the following conversation in 3\u20135 sentences, preserving key facts and decisions.\"},\n            {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": transcript},\n        ],\n        temperature=0,\n    )\n    return rsp.choices[0].message.content\n\ndef trim_history(\n    session: \"ConversationSession\",\n    keep_recent: int = 6,\n    max_tokens: int = 2000,\n) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Return a trimmed message list for the next LLM call.\n    If total estimated tokens > max_tokens, summarise the old turns.\n    \"\"\"\n    system = [m for m in session.messages if m[\"role\"] == \"system\"]\n    history = [m for m in session.messages if m[\"role\"] != \"system\"]\n\n    if session.token_estimate <= max_tokens or len(history) <= keep_recent:\n        return system + history\n\n    old_turns = history[:-keep_recent]\n    recent_turns = history[-keep_recent:]\n    summary = summarise_history(old_turns)\n    summary_message = {\n        \"role\": \"system\",\n        \"content\": f\"[Earlier conversation summary] {summary}\",\n    }\n    return system + [summary_message] + recent_turns\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pattern 4: Persistent Vector Memory"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For long-term personalisation across sessions \u2014 remembering user preferences, prior decisions, or domain-specific facts \u2014 embedding-based memory retrieves relevant past interactions rather than injecting the full history. This keeps prompt size manageable even across hundreds of past sessions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import List\n\n@dataclass\nclass MemoryEntry:\n    memory_id: str\n    user_id: str\n    content: str              # the fact or summary to remember\n    embedding: np.ndarray     # precomputed embedding\n    created_at: float\n\nclass VectorMemoryStore:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._entries: List[MemoryEntry] = []\n\n    def add(self, entry: MemoryEntry) -> None:\n        self._entries.append(entry)\n\n    def recall(\n        self,\n        query_embedding: np.ndarray,\n        user_id: str,\n        top_k: int = 3,\n    ) -> List[MemoryEntry]:\n        user_entries = [e for e in self._entries if e.user_id == user_id]\n        if not user_entries:\n            return []\n        q = query_embedding / (np.linalg.norm(query_embedding) + 1e-9)\n        scored = []\n        for e in user_entries:\n            e_norm = e.embedding / (np.linalg.norm(e.embedding) + 1e-9)\n            score = float(np.dot(q, e_norm))\n            scored.append((score, e))\n        scored.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        return [e for _, e in scored[:top_k]]\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
