      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Stateful complexity should be justified by the use case. Avoid introducing session storage for a single-turn product just because 'we might add chat later'. When chat is added, add the session store \u2014 premature state management is as costly as premature abstraction."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLM APIs are inherently stateless; stateful behaviour is implemented in the system around them. Client-side state is the simplest approach for ephemeral browser sessions; server-side session stores enable multi-device access and audit trails; summarisation bounds prompt growth for long conversations; vector memory enables cross-session personalisation at scale. Every stateful pattern introduces storage, cost, and privacy obligations that must be actively managed. The right choice depends on whether the use case is single-turn or multi-turn, whether sessions are ephemeral or persistent, and how sensitive the conversation content is."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
